definition: "Copper is an essential trace mineral that serves as a catalytic cofactor for numerous metalloenzymes critical to human physiology. Key copper-dependent enzymes include: ceruloplasmin (ferroxidase activity — oxidizes ferrous iron for loading onto transferrin, making copper essential for iron transport); superoxide dismutase-1 (SOD1, the primary cytoplasmic antioxidant enzyme); cytochrome c oxidase (Complex IV of the mitochondrial electron transport chain — essential for ATP production); lysyl oxidase (cross-links collagen and elastin — essential for arterial wall integrity, bone strength, and connective tissue formation); dopamine beta-hydroxylase (converts dopamine to norepinephrine in the catecholamine pathway); and peptidylglycine alpha-amidating monooxygenase (activates neuropeptides and peptide hormones). Serum copper reflects circulating copper, mostly bound to ceruloplasmin. Copper is absorbed in the small intestine, transported to the liver for processing, and distributed to tissues. Copper and zinc compete for intestinal absorption through shared transporters (MT-1/MT-2 metallothioneins), making their balance — the copper-to-zinc ratio — clinically relevant independent of absolute levels."
why_it_matters: "Copper deficiency is rarer than zinc deficiency but produces severe consequences when it occurs — most dramatically, copper deficiency myelopathy, a spinal cord syndrome that mimics vitamin B12 deficiency and can produce irreversible neurological damage before diagnosis. More commonly relevant in longevity medicine is the copper-to-zinc ratio, which has emerged as a clinically useful marker of systemic inflammation and immune dysregulation. Copper is an acute-phase reactant — serum copper rises with inflammation and infection, while zinc falls. The ratio therefore rises with inflammatory states. Multiple studies have found that elevated copper-to-zinc ratios are independently associated with cardiovascular mortality, cancer mortality, and all-cause mortality — a finding robust enough that some practitioners use it alongside traditional cardiovascular markers. Paradoxically, copper excess — typically from dietary supplements, copper pipes, or Wilson's disease — produces hepatotoxicity, neurological damage, and prooxidant effects via the Fenton-like chemistry that generates hydroxyl radicals from copper-catalyzed hydrogen peroxide reduction."

standard_range: "70–140 µg/dL (serum copper)"
